{"plugins":{"posthtml-include":{"root":"./src"},"posthtml-expressions":{"root":"./src/partials","locals":{"top":[{"type":"text","value":"In the wake of the COVID-19 coronavirus pandemic, university administrators and government officials across the world acted to curb the effects of the virus on student populations, evacuating thousands of students from campus and shifting to online courses in a matter of weeks."},{"type":"graphic","value":{"asset":"lede.html","steps":["In the wake of the COVID-19 coronavirus pandemic, university administrators and government officials across the world acted to curb the effects of the virus on student populations, evacuating thousands of students from campus and shifting to online courses in a matter of weeks.","Harvard, Cornell, and Yale were the first Ivies to respond to the coronavirus outbreak by announcing mandatory move-out for students when there were 959 cases nationally.","Columbia University was the last Ivy to announce mandatory move-out, five days after the first Ivies. [ Quadruple TK ]","On average, the Ivy League universities took 8.375 days to respond after the first hundred reported cases in the nation.","This response rate equaled that of <c>China</c>, the first country to begin experiencing an outbreak in late January. 8 days after the first hundred reported cases, when the national number of cases had reached 2,863, the government mandated the closure of all schools.","The Ivies’ responses were far slower than that of <c>South Korea</c>, which began experiencing an outbreak in late February. The South Korean government closed schools across the country when there were 602 cases, 2 days after the first hundred reported cases.","The number of national cases at the time of Columbia’s response matches that of Italy, which has faced significant criticism for its delays. Italy began experiencing an outbreak in early March. They responded by closing schools when there were 3,858 cases, 11 days after the first hundred reported cases."]}}],"credits":"","footer":"<a href=\"https://www.columbiaspectator.com/contributors/Griffin-Jones\">Griffin Jones</a> contributed reporting. Produced with <a href=\"https://github.com/spec-journalism/spectate/\">Spectate</a>.","headline":"The U.S. and Ivy League schools were late to respond to COVID-19. Data shows international universities did better.","date":"April 10, 2020","byline":"By <a href=\"https://www.columbiaspectator.com/contributors/Kelly-Pu/\">Kelly Pu</a>, <a href=\"https://www.columbiaspectator.com/contributors/Jun-Yi-Zhang/\">Jun Yi Zhang</a>, <a href=\"https://www.columbiaspectator.com/contributors/Stephanie-Lai/\">Stephanie Lai</a>, <a href=\"https://www.columbiaspectator.com/contributors/Raeedah-Wahid/\">Raeedah Wahid</a>\nProduced by <a href=\"https://www.columbiaspectator.com/contributors/Hong-Sen-Du/\">Hong Sen Du</a> and <a href=\"https://www.columbiaspectator.com/contributors/Jason-Kao/\">Jason Kao</a>\nEdited by <a href=\"https://www.columbiaspectator.com/contributors/Karen-Xia\">Karen Xia</a>","body":[{"type":"text","value":"Public health experts raised concerns over U.S. schools’ slow reactions to the COVID-19 pandemic, citing a lack of national and international coordination, widespread lack of preparation for the evolving virus by U.S. institutions, and miscommunication between the government and universities."},{"type":"text","value":"Trends from Ivy League schools revealed no uniform response, which public health experts said mirrored that of universities across the nation, attributing it to the lack of uniform national direction. In light of the pandemic, the Ivy League helped shape conversations among higher education institutions and their response rates highlighted the national trend."},{"type":"subhed","value":"Columbia"},{"type":"graphic","value":{"asset":"columbia-graphic.html"}},{"type":"subhed","value":"Ivies react to suspected COVID-19 cases among peer institutions"},{"type":"text","value":"Most universities reported a positive case among a college affiliate around the second week of March and subsequently reacted at a similar rate. Many Ivy League schools seemed to follow suit after Columbia’s initial response, yet <b>Columbia was the last to force students to vacate campus."},{"type":"text","value":"</b>"},{"type":"graphic","value":{"asset":"schools.html"}},{"type":"text","value":"According to public health experts, U.S. school administrators were prompted to take action by suspected or confirmed cases within their respective communities rather than taking precautionary measures. Consequently, their actions lagged behind those taken by their counterparts in other countries which saw the impact of COVID-19 prior to the United States."},{"type":"text","value":"Across the Ivies, Spectator found universities also responded to the first case in their state at differing rates, which experts said resulted from lack of federal guidance on handling the virus. Countries like China and Italy, on the other hand, had a unified response."},{"type":"text","value":"Bernadette Boden-Albala, the dean of Public Health at the University of California, Irvine, attributed the U.S. and many of its universities’ delayed responses to misinformation and the evolving understanding health experts had on the virus."},{"type":"text","value":"“Early countrywide public health decisions were delayed, and there are consequences to those early delays,” Boden-Albala said."},{"type":"text","value":"The delay in U.S. response may also be the result of lack of international communication and coordination, said School of International Affairs professor Robert Jervis."},{"type":"text","value":"“There’s been no attempt from us to lead international coordination [in] any way,” Jervis said, citing the country’s decision to cancel flights from Europe without consulting the countries impacted by the travel ban before the announcement."},{"type":"text","value":"While other countries took after China as a model of combatting the virus, the United States mostly waited for the virus to escalate before taking reactionary measures due to the general misunderstanding of the scope of the virus, Boden-Albaba said. She noted that much of the U.S. public had seen China’s tactics as extreme."},{"type":"text","value":"“We were all surprised when China decided to lock down an entire province, it seemed almost inconceivable,” Jervis added."},{"type":"text","value":"Boden-Albala said many U.S. universities failed to take proactive measures to better inform students, including campaigns on how to prepare for the virus through handwashing and transmission prevention."},{"type":"text","value":"“Universities should have taken action earlier to make sure students were more informed to decrease viral spread—focusing on influenza if nothing else because the same practices are still the same one that would stop transmission of coronavirus,” she said. <b>"},{"type":"text","value":"</b><b>"},{"type":"text","value":"</b>While universities waited for public health officials to send them messages to shut down, administrators took additional measures to ensure students suspected to have come in contact with the virus self-quarantined, and they canceled events."},{"type":"text","value":"Columbia requested students not to gather in groups of 25 people on March 5, but still had not canceled classes, leaving faculty members unsure if their classes would still function."},{"type":"text","value":"For University students—who believed the virus had no effect on them—the messaging from administrators and the public left <a href=\"https://www.columbiaspectator.com/news/2020/03/30/inconsistent-messaging-around-young-peoples-covid-19-risk-contributes-to-spread-of-infection/\">students misinformed</a> over the risks of the virus and preventative measures."},{"type":"text","value":"At the University of Pennsylvania, administrators sent out two different move-out dates, March 15 and 17 and moved commencement online but later changed their mind to postpone it. These actions may have contributed to the spread of misinformation on the impact of the virus to students."},{"type":"text","value":"Similar actions were taken at Columbia, Yale, Princeton, and Dartmouth. These universities originally only announced remote classes for a few weeks and later extended them to the entire semester in order to respond to the rapidly changing nature of the virus as recommended by government officials. At the time of the initial announcement, students may not have understood the severity of the situation until weeks later when they were forced to evacuate."},{"type":"text","value":"<i>Kelly Pu is a Graphics deputy editor at Spectator. She can be contacted at </i><a href=\"mailto:kelly.pu@columbiaspectator.com\"><i>kelly.pu@columbiaspectator.com</i></a><i>."},{"type":"text","value":"</i><i>"},{"type":"text","value":"</i><i>Jun Yi Zhang is a Graphics reporter at Spectator. She can be contacted at </i><a href=\"mailto:junyi.zhang@columbiaspectator.com\"><i>junyi.zhang@columbiaspectator.com</i></a><i>. Follow her on Twitter </i><a href=\"https://twitter.com/jsonkao\"><i>@jsonkao</i></a><i>."},{"type":"text","value":"</i>"},{"type":"text","value":"<i>Stephanie Lai is a News editor at Spectator. She can be contacted at </i><a href=\"mailto:stephanie.lai@columbiaspectator.com\"><i>stephanie.lai@columbiaspectator.com</i></a><i>. Follow her on Twitter </i><a href=\"https://twitter.com/stephaniealai\"><i>@stephaniealai</i></a><i>."},{"type":"text","value":"</i><i>"},{"type":"text","value":"</i><i>Raeedah Wahid is the Graphics editor at Spectator. She can be contacted at </i><a href=\"mailto:raeedah.wahid@columbiaspectator.com\"><i>raeedah.wahid@columbiaspectator.com</i></a><i>. Follow her on Twitter </i><a href=\"https://twitter.com/raeedahwahid\"><i>@raeedahwahid</i></a><i>."},{"type":"text","value":"</i><i>"},{"type":"text","value":"</i>"}],"USE_EYE_NAV":false,"USE_COVER_HED":false,"DOC_URL":"https://docs.google.com/document/d/1fNrjjrx3_Aesq-TBY0Y1cZQxz44z02mVj0dn2siff-g/edit?usp=sharing"}}}}
